SIMPLE: purpose
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Purpose
<hw>Pur"pose</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>purpos</ets>, <ets>pourpos</ets>, <ets>propos</ets>, L.
<ets>propositum</ets>. See <er>Propound</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>That which a person sets before himself as an object to be reached
or accomplished; the end or aim to which the view is directed in any
plan, measure, or exertion; view; aim; design; intention;
plan.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He will his firste <qex>purpos</qex> modify.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As my eternal <qex>purpose</qex> hath decreed.</q> <rj><qau>
Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The flighty <qex>purpose</qex> never is o'ertook⟦br⟧
Unless the deed go with it.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Proposal to another; discourse.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Instance; example.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>In purpose</b></col>, <col><b>Of purpose</b></col>,
<col><b>On purpose</b></col></mcol>, <cd>with previous design; with the
mind directed to that object; intentionally. <xex>On purpose</xex> is
the form now generally used.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- design; end; intention; aim. See
<er>Design</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purpose</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Purpose
<hw>Pur"pose</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Purposed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Purposing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>purposer</ets>,
<ets>proposer</ets>. See <er>Propose</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
set forth; to bring forward.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To propose, as an aim, to one's self; to determine
upon, as some end or object to be accomplished; to intend; to design; to
resolve; -- often followed by an infinitive or dependent clause.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Did nothing <qex>purpose</qex> against the state.</q> <rj><qau>
Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>purpose</qex> to write the history of England from the
accession of King James the Second down to a time which is within the
memory of men still living.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purpose</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Purpose
<hw>Pur"pose</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To have a purpose or intention;
to discourse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purposedly</ent>⟦br⟧
